      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why R-Words Matter in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>R appears six times in the bag — only E, A, I, and O appear more frequently. This abundance means R is almost always available, making it the foundation of consistent scoring. While individual R plays won't match the explosive scores of Q or Z words, R enables the bingo plays (using all 7 tiles for a 50-point bonus) that swing games decisively.</p>
      <p>The RE- prefix alone opens up hundreds of valid words: REZONE, REMIX, REFIX, REWAX. Combined with R's natural partnership in consonant clusters (BR, CR, DR, FR, GR, PR, TR), it's the most connective consonant in Scrabble. Players who master R-words maintain scoring consistency turn after turn.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing R-Words</h2>
      <p>R's strength is flexibility, not raw points. Here's how to maximise your R-word game:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Pair R with high-value tiles:</strong> RAZZ (22 pts), REX (10 pts), RAJ (10 pts) — R combined with Z, X, or J creates compact power plays. Always look for these combinations first.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Use RE- for board extension:</strong> Almost any existing word can potentially gain RE- at the front. This lets you build off opponents' words while scoring through premium squares they missed.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Keep R for bingo potential:</strong> R appears in more 7-letter combinations than any other consonant. If your rack has good bingo material (balanced vowels/consonants plus R), consider holding it for the 50-point bonus.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>-ER suffix hooking:</strong> Add -ER to existing words on the board (FAST → FASTER, PLAY → PLAYER). This creates scoring opportunities from opponents' previous plays.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>RH- words for vowelless racks:</strong> RHYTHM (17 pts) uses no standard vowels. When your rack is consonant-heavy, RH- words rescue you from exchanging tiles.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The RE- Prefix: Your Swiss Army Knife</h2>
      <p>RE- is arguably the most productive prefix in Scrabble. It means "again" and can be attached to hundreds of base words. Key RE- words for scoring:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>REFIX (15 pts), REWAX (15 pts), REMIX (14 pts):</strong> RE- plus high-value letters create mid-teens scores in just 5 letters</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>REZONE (15 pts), REZONED (17 pts):</strong> RE- with Z delivers strong scores while using common tiles</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>REFLUX (16 pts), REFLEX (16 pts):</strong> RE- with X at the end creates satisfying word shapes that fit many board positions</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Managing Multiple R Tiles</h2>
      <p>With six R tiles in the bag, you'll sometimes draw two or three at once. Unlike vowel-heavy racks, double-R isn't necessarily a problem — words like RARER, MIRROR, and ERROR exist. But triple-R is a sign to exchange. Keep one R for flexibility and swap the extras for fresh tiles that complement your remaining rack.</p>
      <p>The ideal rack has exactly one R alongside a mix of vowels and varied consonants. This maximises your chances of forming seven-letter words and hitting the bingo bonus that wins close games.</p>

